snapraid-daily (1.5.1-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Fixed Minor Issue where printouts were incorrectly counting
    the number of hook scripts called at the end. Closes [#3].

  * Debian Package Related Updates:

    - Configured debian/rules to call dh_installsystemd with the
      options not to start or enable the systemd service and
      timer files upon installation, and also not to stop or
      restart them upon upgrades. Timer files need to manually
      started. This is of course intended as the config file
      has to be configured anyway.

    - Switched to using debhelper tokens in postinst and
      prerm maintainer scripts.

    - Deleted postrm script as its no longer required.

    - Refined check on hook naming in the config file in the
      postinst script so that the config file hook script
      naming (start_hook -> start_hook1) is only updated if upgrading
      from a version < 1.5.0.

    - Also implemented the above check on removing old unmodified
      systemd unit files from /etc/systemd/system.

    - Changed debian/copyright to cover all files to clear up
      lintian warning on source package.

    - Modified debian/rules with comments to clear up some lintian
      warnings.

    - Added debian/po/POTFILES.in and modified templates to enable
      translations. Unlikely that this will be translated, but good
      to have!

    - Also added a build dependency on po-debconf.

    - Refined prompt messages.

    - Package is now completely Lintian clean and thus fully in line
      with Debian standards!

 -- Mark <mark9000@fastmail.org>  Sun, 03 Aug 2025 20:17:39 +0100

snapraid-daily (1.5.0-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * Added support for multiple hooks! The script can now call up to 5
    start, end and notification hooks. This greatly expands the ability
    for customisation. Closes [#2].

  * Renamed hook script variables to add numbers to enable this change:
    - start_hook to start_hook1
    - end_hook to end_hook1
    - notification_hook to notification_hook1
    If installed via the package, the debian/postinst script will make an
    edit to the config file to update the naming, such that the upgrade
    should be seamless. If not installed via the package, one will have to
    manually change the hook naming in the config file.

  * Note however the update of the config file will only work on the default
    config file location - /etc/snapraid-daily.conf. If one is using a 
    config file in another location, updating the config file manually is
    required.
    - See the updated documentation on the hooks.

  * The User is now prompted to enter a user name and group upon installing
    the debian package. This is to automate running the service as a user
    other than root if desired.

  * Script result is now printed as "Warning" if errors are encountered
    while running the end hook(s). However the script will still run to the
    end as before.

  * Updates to Manual Entries: snapraid-daily(1) and snapraid-daily.conf(1)

  * Fixed issue where the notification hooks were not called if the script
    ended in a Warning condition with the disable_emails_on_success parameter
    enabled.

  * Systemd unit files are now installed in /usr/lib/systemd/system as is
    now the case with Debian, updated postinst script to handle this.
    - On older versions, if installed via the package the unit files were
      installed in /etc/systemd/system. If they still exist there without
      modification, the postinst script will move them to the new location,
      otherwise they are left unchanged.
    - Does not effect manual installations.

  * Debian Package updates:
    - Fixed dpkg-source warnings while building the package. Package is no
      longer regarded as a native debian package.
    - Updated debian/control dependencies, snapraid-daily-hooks (>=0.3.3)
      is now suggested instead for full compatibility.
    - Removed unused dependency for findutils. It was originally included
      for xargs which is no longer used.
    - Added a Pre-Depends dependency for debconf to implement the prompts
      during installation.
    - Updated debian/postinst script to implement the prompts for a user
      and group, and also to handle checking the config file for new
      hook naming syntax.
    - Added a postrm script to purge debconf and also remove config files
      not already removed through the purge operation.
    - Removed printouts from prerm script.
    - Moved sample config to examples folder to fix .conf extension having
      it converted to a different format on package based installs.
    - Removed build dependency on dh-exec.
    - Lintian check completed on package.

  * The pace of updates should now slow down, as most features that were
    planned to be added have now been added.
    - Feel free to raise an issue on Github if you have any suggestions! 

 -- Mark <mark9000@fastmail.org>  Tue, 29 Jul 2025 21:12:41 +0100

snapraid-daily (1.4.3-1) stable; urgency=medium

  * In the unlikely case for the default run of a sync followed by a 
    scrub, the script would report everything is okay if changes in
    the array were still found directly after the sync operation. Now
    the script will exit with an error and report this to the user. 

  * Moved default systemd unit files to /lib/systemd/system from 
    /etc/systemd/system

  * The debian/postinst script has been updated to check for service and
    timer files in /etc/systemd/system and handle the change in location.
    - If user modification of those files is found, the old files are
      left behind untouched.
    - If on the other hand, user modification is not found, the old files
      are deleted in favor of the new location.
    - This should be seemless as by default precedence is given to
      /etc/systemd/system by systemd.

  * Update manpage to mention the new default location for the service
    unit files, add details about the default run times for the 
    bundled timer files, and how to adjust them as this was previously
    not discussed.

  * Update description in debian/control.

